In [[telecommunication]], a '''comparably efficient interconnection''' (CEI) is an [[Unbundled access|equal-access]] concept developed by the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]] stating that, ". . . if a [[common carrier|carrier]] offers an [[enhanced service]], it should be required to offer [[telecommunications network|network]] [[interconnection]] (or [[Colocation (business)|colocation]]) opportunities to others that are comparably efficient to the interconnection that its enhanced service enjoys. Accordingly, a carrier would be required to implement CEI only as it introduces new enhanced services." [FCC ''Report and Order'' June 16, 1986]
