{{Infobox court case | name = Tertiary Institutes Allied Staff Assoc Inc v Tahana | court = [[Court of Appeal of New Zealand]] | date_filed = | image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg | date decided = 14 August 1997 | full name = Tertiary Institutes Allied Staff Association Incorporated v Tahana | citations = [1998] 1 NZLR 41 | judges = [[Kenneth Keith|Keith J]], [[Peter Blanchard|Blanchard J]], [[Silvia Cartwright|Cartwright J]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = | Keywords = negligence }}
'''''Tertiary Institutes Allied Staff Assoc Inc v Tahana''''' [1998] 1 NZLR 41 is a cited case in [[New Zealand]] regarding the legal defence of judicial proceedings regarding defamation claims in [[tort]].<ref name="McLay">{{cite book |title=Butterworths Student Companion Torts |edition=6th |last1=McLay |first1=Geoff |publisher=LexisNexis |ISBN=9781877511400|year=2010 |page=}}</ref>
==Background== Unhappy with the performance of the Chief Executive Mr Tahana, of the [[Waiariki (New Zealand electorate)|Waiariki]] polytech, the Tertiary Institutes Allied Staff Association lodged a complaint with the polytech's council.
As a result of this complaint, Tahana sued the association for [[defamation]]. They in turn defended the claim on the grounds of being absolutely privileged under section 14 of the Defamation Act, which covers matters raised judicially, such as a court proceedings.
==Held== The court held that the Polytech's tribunal did not meet the threshold of being "judicial", and the associations defence failed.
